The district will be monitoring the metrics and hoping that the COVID-19 activity level metric falls.

post_text:
Young Adult Employment Opportunity
White Pass High School is looking to place up to eight young adults into employment positions with area companies and businesses using Grant, Government, and Private Funding Sources. This opportunity will allow students to learn technical and work-related skills that will further future employment potential.
White Pass High School is recruiting for 8 positions within age ranges from 17 to 19 years old. The job internships could be up to 160 hours. Work duties may include: Customer Service, Physical Labor, use of Tools & Machinery, and Computers. If you are interested in Summer Employment, please contact Debbie Layman at 360-520-7171 for questions regarding the application process.
Anticipated start date is July 27th.

post_text:
GEARUP has 2 great virtual summer camps coming up.

MADLearn Camp: Mobile App Development
June 22 -26, 2020

This camp provides a unique and engaging experience where you will develop your very own mobile app!

Campers will build a working app, complete with their own visual design and content that is ready to be viewed on their iOS or Android device. At the end of the week, there will be a virtual MAD-shark tank where students will present the apps they have built and compete to win an amazing prize!

*PLUS* daily drawings for prizes and a ($$) reward for perfect attendance throughout the week!

LEADERSHIP CAMP: College fit, Career exploration, Collaboration, Leadership
JUNE 22-24, 2020

This three-day program is an experience designed for GEAR UP students! Join us if you‚Äôd like to enhance lifelong employability skills and get yourself ready for future success in both college and the working world through activities and challenges. Plus, your favorite FOCUS trainers!

Contact Mrs. Foley to register. mfoley@whitepass.k12.wa.us

post_text:
Good evening, White Pass, families and community. As a result of the governor‚Äôs order for all schools in the state of Washington to be closed through April 24, we wanted you to know that if your child needs to obtain any of their belongings, books or personal items , the elementary and the Jr/Sr high buildings will be open Monday, March 16 and Tuesday, March 17, from 10:00 am until 2:00 pm.

Please access the buildings from the front entrance. The district is in the process of developing plans and determining what options we have In providing services including student meals, learning resources and other support services to the students. This information will be updated by Friday, March 20, 2020.

I want to thank the community for your patience and support as we together face this challenge. Kind regards, keep safe and healthy.

Paul Farris,

Superintendent

Book Release Party!

Come celebrate 6th grade student authors from White Pass Elementary School as they share their new book,

The Struggle for Freedom.
Researched and written as part of a study of American colonialism and the enslavement of African people, this anthology of historical narratives is sure to impress readers of all ages.

Join us as we celebrate entering this book into the browsing collection at Mountain View Timberland Regional Library with a book signing and authors' readings,
5:30-6:30pm Tuesday, March 31, 2020.

Light refreshments will be provided.

Morton School District
May 26, 2019 at 4:01 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to the 12 Morton/White Pass athletes that competed in the State 2B Track Meet at Eastern Washington University in Cheney.
Seniors Tristan Storey, Jesse Urban, Kaleb Rashoff and junior Manuel Martinez won the 400-relay in 43.84, just four-tenths of a second off the meet record. Storey also placed second in both the 100 (11.50 in final - 11.07/PR in prelims) and 200 (22.58/PR in final). Rashoff finished seventh in the long jump (19-9¬Ω), 10th in the 300 hurdles (43.25), and senior Gavyn Higdon was eighth in the javelin (157-9). The Morton/White Pass boys placed seventh in the state with 29 points of the 55 teams represented.
Seniors Elexcious Hampton, Ashley Wurtz, Jacie Dunlap and freshman Jordan Koetje finished 13th in the girls' 800-relay (1:54.50). Dunlap also placed 14th in the 300 hurdles (51.64/PR) and Koetje 16th in the 100 (14.65). Senior Emily Elswick placed 12th in the discus (92-7) as did sophomore Katie Salguero in the shot (30-8¬æ), and senior Kaylen Collette was 13th in the 3200 (13:16).

post_text:
Tuesday, October 22, 2018

Dear Parents/Guardians,

This letter is to inform you that there will be a change in the school calendar beginning October 30, 2018. Tuesday, October 30, 2018 will be the first day of fall conferences instead of October 31, 2018. Therefore, fall conferences will start Tuesday, October 30, 2018 and continue Wednesday and Thursday, October 31st and November 1st, 2018. Friday, November 2, 2018 will be our regular early release day. These days are early release days for students and will follow our regular early release schedule with students being released at 1:30 pm.
It is important that we let you know of this change to the calendar since we will be having early release from school and students will be arriving home early on these days.
Thank you for making accommodations for the change in schedule. Contact your child‚Äôs school if you have a question about the change in schedule, White Pass Elementary (K-6) 360 497-7300, White Pass Jr./Sr. High 360 497-5816.
Sincerely,

Paul Farris
Superintendent
